    <p>Changing careers from a teaching assistant to a teacher is an excellent move if you want to progress. Your classroom experience provides you with relevant skills working with pupils and a realistsic understanding of what life as a teacher is like.</p>
    <h2 class="heading--box-blue">What you'll need to teach in primary or secondary</h2>
    <p>You need <a href="/train-to-be-a-teacher/what-is-qts">qualified teacher status (QTS)</a> to teach in maintained primary, secondary and special schools in England (schools funded by local authorities). You can get this through teacher training.</p>
    <p>You do not need QTS to <a href="/life-as-a-teacher/age-groups-and-specialisms/further-education-teachers">teach in further education</a> or to <a href="/life-as-a-teacher/age-groups-and-specialisms/early-years-teachers">teach in early years</a>.</p>

    <h2 class="heading--box-blue">Qualifications you need to train to teach</h2>
    <div class="check-qualifcations">
  <p>To train to teach in most schools in England, you'll need:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>GCSEs at grade 4 (C) or above in English and maths (and science if you want to teach primary)</li>
    <li>a bachelor's degree in any subject</li>
  </ul>
</div>
